<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_script` (Business Rule)
    row that BLOCKS any transition from a non-Draft status BACK to Draft on the
    `x_casemgmt_case` table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.5.5 verbatim, transition matrix row 7):
        "Any -&gt; Draft: PROHIBITED"
        Failure surface: "Cases cannot be returned to Draft."

    PURPOSE (AAP Section 0.7.4 - VERBATIM ERROR MESSAGE, NON-NEGOTIABLE):
        The literal text "Cases cannot be returned to Draft." MUST appear
        when this guard fires. Character-for-character: capital "C", capital
        "D", trailing period, exact wording. NO smart quotes, NO trailing
        whitespace, NO leading whitespace. The exact wording is the contract.

    THIS BUSINESS RULE IS THE SECOND-PRIORITY TRANSITION GUARD:
        Order=200 places this rule SECOND among the before-update rules in
        this scoped application's full execution chain:

            1) x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml             (order=100, FIRST)
            2) x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition.xml        (order=200, THIS RULE)
            3) x_casemgmt_validate_assigned_agent_membership    (order=300)
            4) x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress    (order=400)
            5) x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml                   (order=500)

        Order=200 ensures terminal-Closed (the more aggressive prohibition
        - "no transitions out of Closed at ALL") is checked FIRST at
        order=100. Once a case is verified as not-Closed, this rule fires
        at order=200 to catch the more specific "Any -&gt; Draft" prohibition.
        Subsequent before-update rules (validate_assigned_agent_membership
        at order=300, clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress at order=400,
        set_closed_date at order=500) never run when this rule aborts
        the action via setAbortAction(true) - the platform short-circuits
        the BR pipeline on abort.

    BEHAVIOR:
        - Trigger          : BEFORE UPDATE only on the `x_casemgmt_case` table
        - Condition        : previous.status !== 'Draft' AND previous.status !== ''
                             AND current.status === 'Draft'
                             AND validateNoBacktransition(prev, next).ok === false
        - Action           : gs.addErrorMessage(result.error) to surface the
                             verbatim message on the form
                             AND current.setAbortAction(true) to cancel the
                             database write
        - Other timing     : does NOT fire on insert (action_insert=false),
                             does NOT fire on delete (action_delete=false),
                             does NOT fire on query (action_query=false)

    WHY action_insert=false:
        Draft is the LEGITIMATE INITIAL STATUS for every new case per the
        dictionary default_value="Draft" on
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml. New cases - whether
        created via the internal form, the Table API, the unauthenticated
        portal submission endpoint
        (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_casemgmt_case_submit.xml), or
        the seed-data scripts under ../seed-data/cases/ - all start at
        Draft. The PROHIBITION is ONLY on the BACK-transition: once a
        case has progressed to Open / In Progress / Pending / Resolved /
        Closed, it MUST NOT return to Draft. A new case being inserted
        with status='Draft' is fine; only existing non-Draft cases being
        UPDATED to Draft are blocked. action_insert=false enforces this
        precisely - the rule simply never fires on insert.

    THE SCRIPT INCLUDE IS THE SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH:
        The script body delegates the validation to
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml's
        validateNoBacktransition(previousStatus, newStatus) method. The
        Script Include encodes the prohibited-transition matrix and the
        verbatim error messages. This BR consumes the Script Include's
        {ok, error} return shape and surfaces the error via
        gs.addErrorMessage() + current.setAbortAction(true). The BR
        itself contains ZERO inline error message strings - the verbatim
        wording lives ONCE in the Script Include and is read from
        result.error here. This single-source-of-truth pattern means a
        future change to the verbatim message (if ever permitted by the
        AAP) requires editing only the Script Include, not every
        consuming BR/flow/UI Action.

    SHARED METHOD WITH BLOCK_TERMINAL_CLOSED:
        validateNoBacktransition(prev, next) handles BOTH prohibited
        patterns from AAP Section 0.5.5:
            - Closed -&gt; non-Closed (terminal-state violation)
              -&gt; "Closed cases are terminal and cannot be modified."
            - non-Draft -&gt; Draft (backtransition violation)
              -&gt; "Cases cannot be returned to Draft."
        The Script Include returns the appropriate verbatim message in
        result.error based on the input arguments. This BR fires only
        when newStatus === 'Draft' AND prevStatus !== 'Draft' (the
        backtransition case); the
        ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml BR fires
        when prevStatus === 'Closed' (the terminal-state case). The two
        BRs cover the two prohibited patterns; the shared Script Include
        centralizes the matrix.

    SCRIPT INCLUDE BEHAVIOR FOR DRAFT -&gt; DRAFT AND INSERT:
        Per the Script Include's documentation and code (see
        ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml lines
        586-619):

            if (prev !== '' &amp;&amp; prev !== 'Draft' &amp;&amp; next === 'Draft') {
                return { ok: false, error: 'Cases cannot be returned to Draft.' };
            }

        The (prev !== '' &amp;&amp; prev !== 'Draft') guard avoids false
        rejections for:
            - INSERT (prev is empty - though insert is also blocked
              upstream by action_insert=false on this BR; the dictionary
              default value places new rows in Draft and this is the
              canonical entry point)
            - Draft -&gt; Draft (no field change; harmless no-op)
        This BR's own pre-check (newStatus === 'Draft' &amp;&amp;
        prevStatus !== 'Draft' &amp;&amp; prevStatus !== '') is redundant with
        the Script Include's logic but acts as a fast-path filter that
        avoids the Script Include instantiation cost on the vast majority
        of updates (those that don't transition to Draft). Defense in
        depth: if the BR's pre-check were ever loosened, the Script
        Include's authoritative matrix would still produce the correct
        result.

    DEFENSIVE PREVIOUS-NULL GUARD:
        The `previous` GlideRecord is null in certain async/system
        contexts (scheduled jobs invoking GlideRecord.update(), some
        bulk import scenarios, server-side script paths that call
        GlideRecord.updateMultiple()). If there is no previous state,
        no transition can be detected, and the rule does nothing. The
        String() cast normalizes the GlideElement to a primitive string
        for safe === comparison; without the cast, GlideElement-vs-string
        equality can behave inconsistently across releases.

    VERBATIM CHOICE LABEL COMPARISON:
        The status comparison uses the EXACT verbatim Title Case label
        defined in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml:
            'Draft' (5 chars, single word, Title Case)
        This MUST match the choice value verbatim per AAP Section 0.5.7.
        ServiceNow Choice fields persist the LABEL string by default
        (not an integer ID), so the comparison is against the label.
        Misspellings such as 'DRAFT' (uppercase, ArkCase Java legacy on
        CaseFile.java line 313's @PrePersist hook), 'draft' (lowercase),
        or 'Drafting' (extended) would silently never match and the rule
        would never fire - a critical correctness concern.

    NO TYPE-FILTER:
        The rule fires for ALL case types (General Inquiry, Complaint).
        The Draft backtransition prohibition is shared across both case
        types per AAP Section 0.5.5 row 7, so per-type filtering would
        be incorrect. The type-specific transition gating is handled by
        the per-type Flow Designer flows
        (../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml and
         ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml); this backtransition
        guard is type-agnostic.

    DEFENSE IN DEPTH:
        The Flow Designer flows enforce transitions through the
        interactive form/UI path (catching what end users attempt). This
        BR catches direct DB modifications via the Table API, scripted
        REST endpoints, GlideRecord scripts, and bulk imports (the paths
        that bypass the form). Both producing the same verbatim error
        message (sourced from the same Script Include) keeps the user
        experience consistent regardless of the entry point. Without
        this BR, an external Table API client could PUT/PATCH a case to
        status=Draft and rewind the case lifecycle, violating the state
        machine contract and corrupting the dashboards (cases that
        rewound through Draft would skew the "Cases opened (30 days)"
        single-score widget which assumes opened_date is monotonic).

    ARKCASE SOURCE-SIDE ANALOG:
        ArkCase's ChangeCaseFileStateService at
        acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java handled state changes via the
        changeCaseState(auth, caseId, newState, ipAddress) method.
        Line 95 set the new status (retval.setStatus(newState)) without
        any guard - the ArkCase service would happily transition any
        case (including Closed cases) to any other state including
        DRAFT. The terminal-state and backtransition behaviors were
        implicit in the Activiti BPMN process definitions and the queue
        handler at CaseFileQueueHandler.java (which set status to
        ACTIVE pre-save). The ServiceNow target makes the Draft
        backtransition prohibition EXPLICIT via this BR plus the Script
        Include's validateNoBacktransition() matrix - a deliberate
        hardening of the case state-machine contract per AAP Section
        0.5.5. The verbatim error message
        "Cases cannot be returned to Draft." is a target-side authored
        string from AAP Section 0.7.4, not sourced from ArkCase.

    NO GLIDERECORD LOOKUPS:
        This BR operates EXCLUSIVELY on the platform-injected `current`
        and `previous` GlideRecord pair (the row being updated and its
        prior state) plus the in-memory Script Include validator
        instance. It performs zero `gs.getReference()` calls, zero
        `GlideRecord.get(sys_id)` calls, and zero `new GlideRecord()`
        instantiations. This is the simplest possible BR shape and
        guarantees no cross-record dependencies that could fail at
        Update Set re-import time.

    EMAIL-DISABLED CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body MUST NOT call gs.eventQueue('...') for any
        email notification event since email is disabled on the PDI.
        This rule contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls, zero gs.email()
        calls, and zero gs.notificationEngine() calls. It performs
        only the validation delegation, gs.addErrorMessage() form-level
        error surface, and current.setAbortAction(true) cancel.

    SCOPED-NAMESPACE CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>     scoped table
        - <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope>            scoped namespace
        - <sys_package>x_casemgmt</sys_package>        scoped application
        - script body references new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator()
                                                       scoped Script Include
        - script body references previous.status        (scoped field)
        - script body references current.status         (scoped field)
        Zero global-scope writes. Zero modifications to OOB tables.

    NO-HARDCODED-SYS_ID CONSTRAINT (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        - <collection> resolves the case table BY NAME (x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_scope> resolves the scope record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - <sys_package> resolves the application record BY NAME (x_casemgmt)
        - The script body resolves the Script Include BY NAME via the
          standard scoped reference syntax
          `new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator()` - no sys_id literal.
        - The script body performs ZERO GlideRecord lookups by sys_id
          literal; it operates only on the platform-injected `current`
          and `previous` GlideRecord pair.
        - The script body uses NO gs.getReference() calls and NO
          GlideRecord.get(sys_id) calls.
        - The <sys_id> element below is THIS record's own deterministic
          primary key (MD5 of "x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition"),
          which is permitted because the AAP "no hardcoded sys_id" rule
          applies to REFERENCE FIELDS pointing at OTHER records, not
          to a record's own primary key.

    UPDATE-SET LOAD ORDER (AAP Section 0.5.2):
        This sys_script record MUST be loaded AFTER:
            - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml             (table this rule attaches to)
            - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml  (field this rule reads via previous/current)
            - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped application)
            - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml           (scope record)
            - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml     (the Draft choice
                                                         value that this
                                                         rule's script
                                                         compares against)
            - ../script_includes/x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator.xml
              (CRITICAL - this BR calls
               new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator().validateNoBacktransition();
               the Script Include MUST exist before this BR fires)
        And BEFORE:
            - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml
              (the demo cases - though seed Update Set imports apply
               rows directly to the database without firing BRs, so
               this rule does not block the initial seeding even when
               cases are seeded with non-Draft status; it does block
               any subsequent UPDATE that attempts to rewind those
               rows back to Draft)
            - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml,
              ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
              (the per-type state-machine flows do not enforce the
               Draft-backtransition rule themselves and rely on this BR
               as the data-layer enforcer)

    DETERMINISTIC SYS_ID:
        sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition")
               = 6396a298689f7e5a5b41ff6afcece502
        32-character lowercase hex. The PDI accepts any valid 32-char
        hex sys_id; deriving from the record name guarantees idempotent
        re-import on a fresh PDI: re-importing the same Update Set
        produces the same sys_id, which collides on the existing record
        and updates it in place rather than creating a duplicate. This
        is the same convention used by the sibling Business Rules:
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed.xml
                sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_block_terminal_closed")
                       = 0ee339c18d12366737a3637b952fe75b
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml
                sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_set_opened_date")
                       = c56aeecd4086f111be2867faae9e55ad
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_closed_date.xml
                sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_set_closed_date")
                       = f6d63b3856121cac9b69215b2c46f64c
            ../business_rules/x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress.xml
                sys_id = MD5("x_casemgmt_clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress")
                       = 0943b10691d8ae86fd3c2fd6994eb693

    VALIDATION GATE MAPPING (AAP Section 0.7.3):
        - Gate 2 (Workflow): "All state transitions enforced for both
          case types - Invalid transitions return blocking error;
          task-closure check blocks Resolved transition". This BR
          enforces the "Any -&gt; Draft is PROHIBITED" rule from AAP
          Section 0.5.5 row 7. The verbatim error
          "Cases cannot be returned to Draft." is mandated by Section
          0.7.4. Without this BR, a script or Table API client could
          change the status of a non-Draft case back to Draft and
          rewind the case lifecycle, violating Gate 2's pass criterion.
        - Gate 6 (Dashboards): "Both dashboards render with synthetic
          data - All widgets display data; no broken report
          references". The Manager View dashboard's "Cases opened (30
          days)" single-score widget at
          ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml COUNTs cases
          where opened_date is within the last 30 days. The widget
          assumes opened_date is monotonic - rewinding a case to
          Draft would not change opened_date, but it would change the
          case's apparent lifecycle stage and cascade misleading
          counts on the "Case count by status" donut and "All cases
          by status" bar reports. This BR's no-rewind guarantee
          underpins those reports' correctness.
        - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Scoped app exported - Update Set
          loads without errors on a fresh PDI instance". The
          deterministic sys_id, reference-by-name pattern, and
          absence of any external lookups guarantee this rule
          re-imports cleanly with zero preview errors.

    NO PII (AAP Section 0.7.2):
        The script body, code comments, description text, and all
        field values contain zero real names, real email addresses,
        real phone numbers, real organizational identifiers, or any
        other personally identifiable information. The rule operates
        exclusively on synthetic case-status enumerations ('Draft')
        and the verbatim error message string returned by the Script
        Include.

    ABORT_ACTION FIELD VS setAbortAction() METHOD:
        Note that the <abort_action>false</abort_action> XML element
        below is the LEGACY pre-Eureka unconditional-abort flag that
        is set to false because we want CONDITIONAL aborting via the
        script body's current.setAbortAction(true) call. The element
        and the script-body method are NOT the same thing - leaving
        <abort_action>false</abort_action> is correct and standard
        for any modern conditional-abort BR.

    CHANGE_FIELDS VS FILTER_CONDITION:
        <change_fields>false</change_fields> means this BR is NOT
        bound to a specific subset of changed fields - it fires on
        ANY update to the row. We use script-level filtering
        (the newStatus === 'Draft' &amp;&amp; prevStatus !== 'Draft'
        check) instead of declarative filter_condition because the
        predicate is on previous.status (the prior value) AND
        current.status (the new value) - ServiceNow's
        filter_condition evaluates against current values only, not
        previous, so it cannot express the cross-state transition
        predicate this rule needs.
-->
<record_update table="sys_script">
    <sys_script action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <abort_action>false</abort_action>
        <access>package_private</access>
        <action_delete>false</action_delete>
        <action_insert>false</action_insert>
        <action_query>false</action_query>
        <action_update>true</action_update>
        <active>true</active>
        <add_message>false</add_message>
        <advanced>true</advanced>
        <change_fields>false</change_fields>
        <client_callable>false</client_callable>
        <collection>x_casemgmt_case</collection>
        <condition/>
        <description>Before-update guard on x_casemgmt_case: blocks any transition from a non-Draft status back to Draft. When current.status === 'Draft' AND previous.status !== 'Draft' AND previous.status !== '', delegates to x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.validateNoBacktransition(previousStatus, newStatus) and surfaces the verbatim error message 'Cases cannot be returned to Draft.' via gs.addErrorMessage() + current.setAbortAction(true) when the validator returns {ok: false}. Per AAP Sections 0.5.5 (transition matrix row 7: 'Any -&gt; Draft: PROHIBITED') and 0.7.4 (verbatim error message - non-negotiable). Order=200 is the SECOND-HIGHEST priority before-update rule in this scoped application; runs AFTER block_terminal_closed (order=100) so terminal-Closed cases short-circuit before this guard, and BEFORE all subsequent housekeeping rules (validate_assigned_agent_membership at 300, clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress at 400, set_closed_date at 500). The Script Include is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for the verbatim error message; this BR contains zero inline error strings. action_insert=false because Draft is the legitimate initial status (per dictionary default_value); only the BACK-transition from a non-Draft state is forbidden. Defensive previous-null guard handles async/system contexts where previous can be null. Skip-if-no-change guard (prevStatus === newStatus) avoids unnecessary Script Include instantiation on non-status-changing updates. Type-agnostic: fires for both General Inquiry and Complaint case types. Defense in depth: the per-type Flow Designer flows do NOT enforce this rule, so this BR is the only enforcer for direct DB modifications via Table API, scripted REST, GlideRecord scripts, and bulk imports. Contains zero gs.eventQueue() calls per the email-disabled constraint and zero hardcoded sys_id literals.</description>
        <execute_function>false</execute_function>
        <filter_condition/>
        <is_rest>false</is_rest>
        <message/>
        <name>x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition</name>
        <order>200</order>
        <priority>100</priority>
        <rest_method/>
        <rest_method_text/>
        <rest_service/>
        <rest_service_text/>
        <rest_variables/>
        <role_conditions/>
        <script><![CDATA[(function executeRule(current, previous /*null when async*/) {
    // Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (transition matrix row 7):
    //     "Any -> Draft: PROHIBITED"
    //     Failure surface: "Cases cannot be returned to Draft."
    //
    // Per AAP Section 0.7.4: the literal text "Cases cannot be returned to
    // Draft." is the VERBATIM, NON-NEGOTIABLE error message surfaced when
    // this guard fires. Character-for-character: capital "C", capital "D",
    // trailing period, exact wording. The message lives ONCE in the Script
    // Include's validateNoBacktransition() return; this BR reads it from
    // result.error and never inlines it.
    //
    // Order=200 makes this the SECOND before-update rule in this scoped
    // application. Order=100 (block_terminal_closed) runs first to catch
    // the more aggressive Closed-terminal prohibition; once that rule has
    // confirmed the case is not Closed, this rule fires at order=200 to
    // catch the more specific Any->Draft case. Subsequent rules
    // (validate_assigned_agent_membership at 300,
    // clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress at 400, set_closed_date at 500)
    // are short-circuited when this rule aborts via setAbortAction(true).
    //
    // Delegates to x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator.validateNoBacktransition()
    // which returns { ok: true } when the transition is allowed, or
    // { ok: false, error: 'Cases cannot be returned to Draft.' } when
    // transitioning TO Draft from a non-Draft state (prev !== '' &&
    // prev !== 'Draft' && next === 'Draft'). The Script Include is the
    // single source of truth for the verbatim message and the prohibited
    // -transition matrix; this BR consumes its return shape and surfaces
    // the error.
    //
    // ArkCase source-side analog: ChangeCaseFileStateService at
    // acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/com/
    // armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/service/ChangeCaseFileStateService.java
    // handled state changes via changeCaseState() (line 95: setStatus)
    // without enforcing a Draft-backtransition rule. Backtransition behavior
    // was implicit in Activiti BPMN process definitions and queue handlers
    // (e.g., CaseFileQueueHandler.java set status to ACTIVE pre-save). This
    // BR makes the rule EXPLICIT at the data layer, hardening the
    // state-machine contract per AAP Section 0.5.5.

    // Defensive previous-null guard: the `previous` GlideRecord is null in
    // certain async/system contexts (scheduled jobs invoking
    // GlideRecord.update(), some bulk import scenarios, server-side script
    // paths that call GlideRecord.updateMultiple()). If there is no previous
    // state, no transition can be detected, and the rule does nothing.
    if (!previous) {
        return;
    }

    // String() cast normalizes the GlideElement to a primitive string for
    // safe === comparison; without the cast, GlideElement-vs-string equality
    // can behave inconsistently across releases. The Title Case literal
    // 'Draft' (5 chars, single word) is the verbatim choice value from
    // ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml per AAP Section 0.5.7. Variants
    // like 'DRAFT' (uppercase, ArkCase Java legacy from CaseFile.java
    // @PrePersist hook), 'draft' (lowercase), or 'Drafting' (extended)
    // would silently never match.
    var prevStatus = String(previous.status);
    var newStatus = String(current.status);

    // Skip if status didn't change - this rule only cares about transitions.
    // Avoids unnecessary Script Include instantiation on the vast majority
    // of UPDATE operations (those that don't change the status field).
    if (prevStatus === newStatus) {
        return;
    }

    // Only fire when transitioning TO Draft from a non-Draft non-empty state.
    // Three conditions, all required:
    //   (1) newStatus === 'Draft'           - we're transitioning toward Draft
    //   (2) prevStatus !== 'Draft'          - we're moving FROM a non-Draft state
    //   (3) prevStatus !== ''               - defensive: empty previousStatus
    //                                         on a brand-new record can't reach
    //                                         this BR because action_insert is
    //                                         false; this guard is belt-and-
    //                                         suspenders for unusual contexts
    //                                         where the platform might emit an
    //                                         empty-string previous.status on a
    //                                         pseudo-update.
    // This BR's pre-check is redundant with the Script Include's authoritative
    // matrix but acts as a fast-path filter to avoid Script Include
    // instantiation cost on the vast majority of updates. Defense in depth:
    // if this pre-check were ever loosened, the Script Include's matrix
    // would still produce the correct result.
    if (newStatus === 'Draft' && prevStatus !== 'Draft' && prevStatus !== '') {
        // Resolve the Script Include via the standard scoped reference syntax.
        // The `x_casemgmt` portion is the scope's vendor_prefix from
        // ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml; the
        // `CaseTransitionValidator` portion is the api_name of the Script
        // Include. NO sys_id literal - the resolution is by scoped class
        // name only.
        var validator = new x_casemgmt.CaseTransitionValidator();
        var result = validator.validateNoBacktransition(prevStatus, newStatus);
        if (!result.ok) {
            // gs.addErrorMessage(result.error) surfaces the verbatim message
            // at the top of the form when the user attempts the save through
            // the UI, and is captured in the API response when the update
            // arrives via Table API or scripted REST. The string is read from
            // result.error - never inlined here - so the verbatim wording
            // contract is enforced by the Script Include alone.
            gs.addErrorMessage(result.error);
            // current.setAbortAction(true) cancels the database write. Both
            // the gs.addErrorMessage() and setAbortAction(true) calls are
            // required: the former produces a visible error to the caller,
            // the latter prevents the write from being persisted. Without
            // setAbortAction(true), the message would appear but the row
            // would still update; without gs.addErrorMessage(), the write
            // would be silently rejected with no visible failure.
            current.setAbortAction(true);
        }
    }
})(current, previous);
]]></script>
        <sys_class_name>sys_script</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
        <sys_domain_path>/</sys_domain_path>
        <sys_id>6396a298689f7e5a5b41ff6afcece502</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_block_draft_backtransition</sys_name>
        <sys_overrides/>
